A Brief Analysis of the Vector Autoregressive Model and its Applications

Rock Pang and Leo Li

1. Introduction

The Vector Autoregressive (VAR) model is one of the most flexible models for the analysis of multivariate time series (Zivot and Wang 2006). Introduced by Christopher A. Sims, a Nobel Prize winner in economics, it has been heavily used in building econometric models (C. A. Sims 1980). Previous literature has studied the correlation of public investment and Gross Domestic Product (Mittnik and Neumann 2001), the market response to the a companys marketing mix (Srinivasan, Vanhuele, and Pauwels 2010), and pass-through effects of exchange rate changes to domestic price (Ito and Sato 2008), etc.

As autoregressive (AR) model use specific lagged values of \(X_t\) as predictors, the VAR model is essentially a combination of univariate AR models. An unique feature of VAR is that a variable depends on not only its own lagged values but also those of other variates in the multivariate vector, and error terms. The problem it tries to tackle is that multiple time series may impact each other at the same time instead of treating an univariate time series as independent. VAR is a complex model to forecast, and one should not think that this method can only be applied to economics. VAR model has been also effective in predicting rainfall (Nugroho, Hartati, and Mustofa 2014), studying of chemical property (Nugroho, Hartati, and Mustofa 2014), and forecasting traffic flow (Kamarianakis and Prastacos 2003), for example.

This tutorial aims to provide detailed introduction of VAR model. In Section 2, we introduce the model. We also discuss the Impulse Response Function and Forecast Error Variance Decomposition, which capture the models dynamic behaviors. In Section 3, we illustrate the VAR model in a real-world example of comparing stock market in mainland China, Hong Kong, the United Kingdom, and the United States. This section contains many useful R codes and graph interpretation. We provide concluding remarks on the advantages and disadvantages of VAR models in general. Then, we discuss how to make more complex models such as Structural VAR model and Bayesian VAR model.

2. Vector Autoregressive Model

VAR models are used for multi-variate time series analysis. As you might recall, an AR(1) model is stated \(X_t = \delta + \phi_1X_{t-1}+\epsilon_t\), where \(\delta\) is a constant, \(\phi_1\) is the AR coefficient, and \(\epsilon_t \stackrel{iid}{\sim} N(0, \sigma_w^2)\) is independent Gaussian white noise with mean 0 and constant variance. In a VAR model, each variable is a linear function of its past lags and past lags of all other variables. A VAR model of lag one, denoted as VAR(1), can be written as the following equations if we consider two time series variables \(x_1\) and \(x_2\):

\[X_{1,t} = \delta_1 + \phi _{1,1}X_{1,t-1} + \phi _{1,2}X_{2,t-1} + \epsilon_{1,t} \\ X_{2,t} = \delta_2 + \phi _{2,1}X_{1,t-1} + \phi _{2,2}X_{2,t-1} + \epsilon_{2,t}\]

Similarly with the same variables, a VAR(2) model can be written as:

\[X_{1,t} = \delta_1 + \phi _{1,1}X_{1,t-1} + \phi _{1,2}X_{2,t-1} + \phi^2 _{1,1}X_{1,t-2} + \phi^2 _{1,2}X_{2,t-2} + \epsilon_{1,t} \\ X_{2,t} = \delta_2 + \phi_{2,1}X_{1,t-1} + \phi_{2,2}X_{2,t-1} + \phi^2_{2,1}X_{1,t-2} + \phi^2_{2,2}X_{2,t-2} + \epsilon_{2,t}\]

where \(\alpha\) is the constat, \(\epsilon\) is the error term and \(\phi^{p} _{i,j}\) denotes the coefficient that explains the relationship between variables \(i\) and \(j\) at the \(p^{th}\) lag. Note that the notation \(\phi_{i,j}^p\) does not indicate the squaring of the coefficient and simply means that the number of lags is equal to \(p\).

Putting the equations above in the matrix form, we get a VAR(2) model as shown below:

\[ \begin{pmatrix} X_{1,t}\\ X_{2,t}\\ \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \alpha_1\\ \alpha_2\\ \end{pmatrix} + \begin{array}{ccc} \begin{pmatrix} \phi _{1,1} & \phi _{1,2}\\ \phi _{2,1} & \phi _{2,2}\\ \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} X_{1,t-1} \\ X_{2,t-1} \\ \end{pmatrix} \end{array} + \begin{pmatrix} \phi^2 _{1,1} & \phi^2 _{1,2}\\ \phi^2 _{2,1} & \phi^2 _{2,2}\\ \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} X_{1,t-2} \\ X_{2,t-2} \\ \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} \epsilon_{1,t}\\ \epsilon_{2,t}\\ \end{pmatrix} \]

To generalize, a \(VAR(p)\) model with \(m\) time series variables will have the following form:

\[ \begin{pmatrix} X_{1,t}\\ X_{2,t}\\ \vdots\\ X_{m,t} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \alpha_1\\ \alpha_2\\ \vdots\\ \alpha_m\\ \end{pmatrix} + \sum_{k=1}^p \begin{pmatrix} \phi^k _{1,1} & \phi^k _{1,2} & ... & \phi^k_{1,m}\\ \phi^k _{2,1} & \phi^k _{2,2} & ... & \phi^k_{2,m}\\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\ \phi^k _{m,1} & \phi^k _{m,2} & ... & \phi^k_{m,m}\\ \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} X_{1,t-k} \\ X_{2,t-k} \\ \vdots\\ X_{m,t-k} \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} \epsilon_{1,t}\\ \epsilon_{2,t}\\ \vdots\\ \epsilon_{m,t} \end{pmatrix} \] Similarly, the \(k\) in the power denotes the number of lags and \(\phi^k_{i,j}\) characterize the relationship between \(i\) and \(j\) at lag \(k\). Note that the summation indicates that for each lag, we would have a unique coefficient matrix and our VAR model includes \(p\) coefficient matrices in total.

The coefficients in the VAR model can be estimated using both Ordinary Least Square and Maximum Likelihood Estimation. In most cases we use MLE instead of OLS but if we assume the errors to be normally distributed, both the OLS and MLE will give us the same results. The interpretation of the coefficient is similar to how we interpret a regular AR model: if \(X_j\) increases by 1 at the \(k^{th}\) lag, then we would expect \(X_i\) to change by the amount of \(\phi^k_{i,j}\) controlling for other variables. However as we can see from the coefficient matrix above, there are too many things going on and the change in one variable is determined by all other variable in different lag periods. Thus interpreting a single coefficient in the VAR model cannot give us much information and thats mainly why we have to go for a another path that could combine all the information in our model to make estimation. The most common tools associated with the VAR model are the Impulse Response Function and the Forecast Error Variance Decomposition, which we will discussed in the next section.

2.1 Impulse Response Function & Forecast Error Variance Decomposition

Once we have a VAR model estimated, we can generate a Impulse Response Function graph to evaluate the dynamics of the system as a whole. Parameters in our VAR models only provide limited information because all variables depend on each other (Mohr 2018). An Impulse Response function deals with the tight correlations. If theres a one-unit shock (a one standard-deviation increase) in the error term of variable (j) at a specific time (t) \(\epsilon_{j,t}\), how would the response variable change accordingly. The impulse response is defined as the derivative of the response value with respect to \(\epsilon_{j,t}\). Before delving into more details, recall that AR(p) can be written as an infinite-order MA model. Similarly, VAR can also be rewritten as VMA(\(\infty\)). It We use VAR(1), rewritten as VMA(\(\infty\)) by successive substitution, as an example to prove the the response change \(\boldsymbol{X_{t}}\) to a shock.

\[\frac{\partial{\boldsymbol{X_{t}}}}{\partial{{\epsilon_{j,t-1}}}} = \frac{\partial}{\partial{\epsilon_{j,t-1}}}(\boldsymbol{\Phi} \boldsymbol{X_{t-1}} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon_{t}}) = \frac{\partial}{\partial{\epsilon_{j,t-1}}} (\boldsymbol{\Phi}(\boldsymbol{\Phi} \boldsymbol{X_{t-2}} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon_{t-1}}) + \boldsymbol{\epsilon_{t}}) = ... = \frac{\partial}{\partial{\epsilon_{j,t-1}}} (\sum_{i=0}^\infty \boldsymbol{\Phi^i \epsilon_{t-i}}) = \boldsymbol{\Phi} e_j\]

In the equation above, \(\boldsymbol{\Phi}\) is the coefficient matrix of VAR(1), which denotes \[\boldsymbol{\Phi} = \begin{pmatrix} \phi_{1,1} & \phi_{1,2} & \dotsi & \phi_{1,m}\\ \phi_{2,1} & \phi_{2,2} & \dotsi & \phi_{2,m}\\ \vdots & \vdots &\ddots & \vdots\\ \phi_{m,1} & \phi_{m,2} & \dotsi & \phi_{m,m} \end{pmatrix}\]

Therefore, the response of a specific value \(X_{i,t}\) to one-time impulse in \(X_{i,t-1}\) hold constant. The response of variable \(i\) to a unit shock in variable \(j\) is sometimes depicted graphically to get a visual impression of the dynamic inter-relationship within the system (Rossi 2011).

To make the Impulse Response Function more refined, we can consider the Orthogonal Impulse Response Function (OIRF). One of the major limitations of the Impulse Response Function is the assumption that there is only a shock to \(\epsilon_{j,t}\) while other terms remain independent. However in most of the cases, a shock to \(\epsilon_{j,t}\) will also lead to a simultaneous shock to \(\epsilon_{i,t}\). As a result, it is hard to measure how much of the response in \(X_{j,t}\) is caused by the shock in \(\epsilon_{j,t}\). In other words, correlation of the error terms may indicate that a shock in one variable is likely to be accompanied by a shock of another variable. Hence we have to eliminate these shocks by using the OIRF (Koop, Pesaran, and Potter 1996). OIRF makes sure that each impulse has no effect on other components because the they are orthogonal.

In R, we can plot this using plot(irf(var_model_name)) to visualize how each variable responds to one shock. We further discuss this in Section 3. One thing to keep in mind, if the plot is stable and close to zero, that means one unit shock in \(x_{i,t}\) has small effect on the other variables at future time.

We can also generate a Forecast Error Variance Decomposition (FEVD) graph based on the VAR model, which shows what portion of the variance of the forecasting errors in predicting a response variable is due to a shock in the impulse variable. It is one way to quantify how important each shock is in explaining the variation in each of the variables in the system (E. Sims, n.d.). The FEVD allows the user to analyze the contribution of variable j to the variance of forecasting error in variable k. The R function will print a bar graph, the larger the portion, the influence of that variable is contributing the most to the forecast uncertainty of the variable of our concern. Section 3 illustrates a specific example of four global stock markets. A rigorous description can be found here.

3. Applications of VAR

VAR models are used extensively in Economics, in which people use techniques such as VAR to conduct causality tests. In this section, we aim to apply the VAR model to estimate the cointegration between different stock markets. Manning (2002) conducted a similar study using the VAR model. He collected data on eight major stock markets in the Southeast Asia and found that there was an increasing integration between these markets from 1988 to 1990 and from 1992 to mid-1997. Here we seek to replicate this study but broaden our horizon to the global stock markets.

Step 1

We collected data on the daily return of four major stock markets gloablly: S&P 500 (the US), Shanghai Stock Exchange (China), Hang Seng Index (Hong Kong), and FTSE 100 (the UK). The time frame of the data is from December 2015 to December 2018 and the source is Yahoo Finance. On Yahoo Finance, the daily opening price and closing price are avaible and we calculated the daily return for each market simply by \(\frac{Closing-Opening}{Opening}\). The daily return of each market will thus be our time series variable \(X\) and each lag is one day. Here we aim to measure the cointegration between these four markets using the VAR model. In other words, we will try to find which markets are more dominant while which markets are being influenced by others if integration does exist.

You should follow this command below to load your data and create time series of your interest. Note that the VAR model in R does not allow NA value, so in this tutorial we approximate the data during the weekends and holidays in different countries by na.approx in library zoo.

library(vars)
library(astsa)
library(zoo)

data <- read_excel("official data2.xlsx", skip = 1)
stocks <- data %>% select(c("s&p500return", "SSEreturn", "HSIreturn", "ftsereturn"))

# US stock market
sp500 <- na.approx(ts(stocks[,1], start=decimal_date(as.Date("2015-12-01")), end=c(2018, 12), frequency=365)) 
# Mainland China stock market
sse <- na.approx(ts(stocks[,2], start=decimal_date(as.Date("2015-12-01")), end=c(2018, 12), frequency=365)) 
# Hong Kong stock market
hsi <- na.approx(ts(stocks[,3], start=decimal_date(as.Date("2015-12-01")), end=c(2018, 12), frequency=365)) 
# The UK stock market
ftse <- na.approx(ts(stocks[,4], start=decimal_date(as.Date("2015-12-01")), end=c(2018, 12), frequency=365))

Then we can visualize our initial time series after combining our time series.

x = cbind(sp500, sse, hsi, ftse)
plot.ts(x , main = "Times series of four major stock markets")

The y-axis measures the daily return of each market as we have mentioned above. If it is 0.02, then it indicates that this market increases by 2% in that coresponding trading day.

Step 2

Theoretically, we have infinite choices of lags, so we would like to use to make a VAR model, we should choose the reasonable lag before delving into the model. In R, VARselect() function will do it for you:

VARselect(x, type = "both")

We can observe four criteria included above. A more detailed comparison can be found here. AIC is the most widely used among the four. However, it is a good practice to select the lag value by examining these criteria and combining this information with additional knowledge specific to the problem (Mullen 2014). Given that each criterion may give different optimal lags, it is in our advantage to fit the models with lags that each criterion suggest and compare them based on our specific context. Using our data, these criteria suggest one-period lag or four-period lag. Considering that we are evaluating stock markets, it makes more sense to use lag=1 given the sponteity of the markets. For instance, the performance of the stock markets at t=1 is highly likely to be correlated with the performance in the next day while the influence will mitigate as we go further. Thus the markets at t=1 are less likely to influence the performance at t=4, and thus a one-period lag is analyzed in this specific context.

In the following R chunk, the p parameter is the lag we choose. An interesting parameter is type which denotes the type of deterministic regressors to include. There are four options const, which stands for constant (or intercept in the model); trend, which considers the trend of the original series; both which includes both constant and trend; or none which includes neither. The choice should also depends on context. In this case, our time series does not seem to have a clear trend, so we use const. (Please see the Appendix for model summary)

fitvar1=VAR(x, p=1, type= "const")

Step 3

Now we examine the ACF of the residuals for after fitting VAR(1) model. Similar to ACF we learned in class, we should pay special attention to see if the ACF falls between the blue dash lines (confidence interval). If so, the series are stationary. If not, we need to decompose the time series to remove trend and seasonality in order to obtain a stationary process. The plots below indicate that the time series have recognizable ACF patterns. In our case, the ACF are approximately fall between the confidence interval.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
acf(residuals(fitvar1)[,1]) #sp500
acf(residuals(fitvar1)[,2]) #sse
acf(residuals(fitvar1)[,3]) #hsi
acf(residuals(fitvar1)[,4]) #ftse

Step 4

Then we can generate Impulse Response functions to describe the response of the four output to an impulse of one stock market in our example. The four OIRF graphs show that based on our data, if there is one-unit shock to one market, how would the other markets respond. Recall that in Section 2.1 by taking the derivative we showed that a one-unit impulse in \(X_i\) will lead to a certain amount of change in \(X_j\) in the first lag period. While our proof only demonstrates this pattern for the first lag but for other lag periods the proof is the same and each lag period has an associated coefficient that determines the amount of change in \(X_j\) in this period if an impulse is given to \(X_i\). Here in our example, the x-axis is lag which is one day in this case. The y-axis shows by how much each market would react in each lag period if we impose a one-unit shock to a market at lag \(t=0\).

par(mfcol = c(2, 2))
plot(irf(fitvar1, impulse = "sp500", ortho = TRUE)) 
plot(irf(fitvar1, impulse = "sse", ortho = TRUE))
plot(irf(fitvar1, impulse = "hsi", ortho = TRUE))
plot(irf(fitvar1, impulse = "ftse", ortho = TRUE))

In the first graph, we can see that if there is a unit shock to S&P 500 at t=0, all the other three markets will respond accordingly. In particular, FTSE (Britain) have the largest response at both t=1 and t=2, while SSE and HSI have a less volatile response. It makes sense intuitively because as the largest stock market in the world, the movements in S&P 500 are very likely to affect other stock markets that have a smaller volume.

From the second graph we can see that a shock to the SSE (mainland China) will have a significant influence on the HSI (Hong Kong) while not impacting the other two markets. This observation also makes sense given that the mainland China and Hong Kong are closely related to each other and given the larger volume of the Shanghai Stock Exchange, its very likely to impact Hong Kong stock market.

From the third graph we can see that given an impulse in HSI (Hong Kong), only the FTSE (Britain) market shows a noticeable response at t=1, while the other two markets seem unchanged. Even though mainland China and Hong Kong are closely related, the performance of HSI will not impact the performance of SSE given the difference in the market volume we mentioned before.

Based on the last graph, we notice that an impulse in the FTSE (Britain) will not have any major impact on the other three markets, which makes sense because among these four markets the British market has the smallest volume and thus it is unlikely to influce other bigger markets.

Step 5

Then, we can generate the Forecast Error Variance Decoposition (FEVD) to determine the influence of each shocks by looking at the portion of each stock market in the bar graph.

plot(fevd(fitvar1, n.ahead = 5))

The FEVD graphs give us similar results as what we have found in the OIRF graphs. We can see that the almost all of the variance of forecasting errors in predicting S&P 500 and SSE (mainland China), which are the two largest markets, comes from themselves, which indicates that these two markets are barely influenced by oter markets. However about 40% of the variance of forecasting errors in predicting HSI (Hong Kong) comes from SSE (mainland China), which indicates that HSI has been influenced a lot by SSE. Similarly, around 40% of the variance of forecasting errors in predicting FTSE (Britain) comes from S&P 500 (U.S.), indicating that the U.S. stock market has a significant influence on the British stock market. The FEVD graphs also suggest that S&P 500 and SSE are the two most dominant stock markets globally and more specifically, S&P 500 tends to have a significant impact on FTSE and SSE tends to have a significant impact on HSI.

Step 6

Finally, we can predict the next few days of stock price changes in the next few days based on our VAR model. This is our ultimate goal in variable prediction using VAR after considering the correlations between multiple time series. Below are codes and nice picture of the predictions of the stock price changes in the next 5 days.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
predictions <- predict(fitvar1, n.ahead = 5, ci = 0.95)
plot(predictions, xlim = c(700, 800), names = "sp500")
plot(predictions, xlim = c(700, 800), names = "sse")
plot(predictions, xlim = c(700, 800), names = "hsi")
plot(predictions, xlim = c(700, 800), names = "ftse")

4. Conclusion

The tutorial poject provides an overview on the VAR Model, the asociated Impulse Response Function and Forecast Error Variance Decomposition. Then we apply these techniques in a real world setting and try to figure out the cointegration of the four major stock markets. VAR models are useful tools in many fields in that it evaluates multivariate time series and checks their influence on each other at different lags. It models the dynamic response to shocks in the Impulse Response function. It can aid identification of shocks and determines the corresponding effects on other variables after a certain period of time. This is especially informative in analyzing policy shocks to form an economic policy. It is often considered good for short-term forecasting.

VAR, however, has its disadvantages too. When we add more variables in the model, the number of parameters goes rapidly. If we fit too many variables and lags in the model, it also tend to be overfitting. Multicollinearity can also become a serious problem as more series and lagged values of series are added to the model. It can be very difficult to separate the effects between variables.

The flexibility of the VAR model enables it to be modified in some cases into a Structural VAR model or a Bayesian VAR model depending on our objectives. Compared to the regular VAR model, a Structural VAR model assumes that every error term has mean zero and there is no correlation between each error term across time. With that being said, the off-diagonal entries in the covariance matrix of a SVAR model are all zero. In other words, a SVAR better isolate the serial correlation in our data and thus it is more often used in evaluating economic policies when we have to control for correlation and multicollinearity.

Similarly to the gap between Bayesian Statistics and Frequentist, a Bayesian VAR model views the model parameters as random variables and takes into account a prior information. In our example, a Bayesian VAR model may have a better estimation because we have a strong prior knowledge in the fact that larger markets tend to impact smaller markets. Whats more interesting, in macroeconomics one of the most commonly used priors in the BVAR model is called the Minnesota Prior, in which we assume that the coefficients in the model follow a random walk bahavior and normal distribution given the randomness of most economic data.

In short, the VAR model has become one of the most prevalent techniques in the time series analysis. We hope that this tutorial project may have offered you some insights into the time series analysis not only in economics but also many other fields.
